\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <I> <#/>}{\b\fs24\lang2057 <h> Mother Africa gives birth to Namibia </h>
\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>THE sun set on Africa's last colony today when racist South Africa lowered its flag over Namibia to make way for the world's newest independent nation.
\par }\pard\plain \s16\qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \v\lang2057 {\v0 <#/>Scores of foreign del
egations flocked into Windhoek, capital of the vast desert territory to see Pretoria hand over power at midnight (2200 GMT) to a government led by the militant South-West Africa People's Organisation (Swapo).
\par }\pard\plain \qj\nowidctlpar\adjustright \fs20\lang1031 {\fs24\lang2057 <#/>UN Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuella
r, who arrived on Monday, presided over celebrations which bring to an end the world body's most expensive and most successful peacekeeping operation.
\par <#/>The UN mission to supervise the transition to independence began in near-disaster last April when South African troops killed hundreds of Swapo guerrillas who had crossed the border from Angola.
\par <#/>In Namibia, bitter recriminations have now given way to reconciliation.
\par <#/>"Today, I return to take part in the celebration of a hope fulfilled. <#/>The world now speaks of a Namibian model in praise of the restraint, tolerance and political maturity demonstrated by Namibians," Perez de Cuellar said on arrival.
\par <#/>Independent Namibia's first President Sam Nujoma, who led Swapo in its 23-year guerrilla war aga
inst Pretoria's illegal occupation, accepted the reins of government from his old adversary, South African apartheid leader F.W. de Klerk, at the independence ceremony.
\par <#/>Meetings between the scores of world leaders and officials attending the celebrations were also scheduled to take place during the celebrations.
\par <#/>Windhoek, a small quiet town with a Germanic colonial favour, has also become an incongruous venue for world leaders to assess the results of Sunday's East German elections, won by the pro-unification Conservative alliance.
\par <#/>US Secretary of State James Baker and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze were to meet this evening and Baker was scheduled to have talks with West German Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher the following day.
\par <#/>Earlier Baker was to have held talks with Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, the highest-level meeting ever between the two countries.
\par <#/>Top of the agenda would be Luanda's 15-year civil war with bandits of the so-called National Union for the Total Independence of Angola (Unita), which has <-/intesified> following an <-/arbotive> ceasefire last year.
\par <#/>Freed African National Congress (ANC) leader Nelson Mandela was also expected to meet Baker and other western officials.
\par <#/>Mandela had refused to meet Baker in South Africa, the US Secretary of State's next stop, because of the ANC's policy of promoting South Africa's political, diplomatic and economic isolation.
\par <#/>But he had indicated readiness to talk to Baker and other leaders in Namibia now that Pretoria has relinquished control there.
\par <#/>South African racist President F.W. <#/>de Klerk and Angolan President <ea/>Ndugu Jose Eduardo dos Santos held talks this morning in Windhoek, hours before Namibia declared her independence from South Africa.
\par <#/>The meeting, which was also attended by the foreign ministers of the two countries, was de Klerk's first in a series of talks arranged with African leaders for the day.
\par <#/>No details of the talks are available. <#/>But the two leaders briefly discussed the ongoing military conflict between Angolan Government forces and the anti-government bandits of Unita.
\par <#/>The South African apartheid leader will also meet with two European ministers whose identities have not yet been revealed.
\par <#/>De Klerk was also scheduled to meet with United Nations Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar this afternoon.
\par <#/>Meanwhile, reports from Lagos said the Nigerian Federal Government has appointed Major-General Joseph Garba as the first Nigerian ambassador to Namibia, the News Agency of Nigeria (NAN) reported yesterday. </I>
