\par }{\fs24\lang2057 <#/>MINIMUM wage earners will get a 40 per cent rise in addition to tax <-_reliefs><+_relief> and a range of policy measures to reduce the cost of living and improve social welfare.
\par <#/>The package is part of the 1991/92 government budget proposals tabled in the National Assembly in Dar es Salaam yesterday by Finance Minister Steven Kibona.
\par <#/>He told the House that the wage rise would diminish to 15 per cent for the highest paid civil servants. <#/>The new minimum wage, effective July, computes to 3,500/-.
\par <#/>Family tax relief will rise to 100/- from 60/- monthly in July while 50/- will be retained for each child, up from 10/-.
\par <#/><ea/>Ndugu Kibona said civil servants in Dar es Salaam would draw 1,000/- monthly transport allowance instead of 700/-.
\par <#/>Government employees will benefit from housing, furniture and car loans to be introduced in the new financial year. <#/>The furniture and car loans would be managed by the Treasury while the Tanzania Housing Bank will administer the housing fund.

\par <#/>The Minister proposed to reduce Customs duty and sales tax on sugar from 30 to 20 per cent and waive the tax on bread, tractor tyres and bottle coolers.
\par <#/>"It is the hope of the Government that these measures will benefit the consumer," he said. <#/><ea/>Ndugu Kibona told a press briefing earlier that the tax reductions were intended to lower consumer prices.
\par <#/>He told the House that importers of buses intended to serve the rural areas would be exempted from customs duty and sale tax after registering with regional authorities.
\par <#/>Tanzanians returning after staying abroad for more than one year will not pay customs duty on their imports, including one car. <#/>Tax exemption on car applies once every four years.
\par <#/>Meanwhile, the Government has proposed three funds for road maintenance, housing and plots development.
\par <#/><ea/>Ndugu Kibona told the National Assembly that the roads fund would draw 5/50 of the 7/- road toll charged on every litre of petrol and diesel in the new financial year as an interim measure.
\par <#/>The remaining 1/50 collected from each litre will be used to maintain regional roads under supervision of the Ministry of Regional Administration and Local Governments.
\par <#/>The Minister said in the long-term the roads fund would be sustained by vehicle registration, road licence, vehicle transfer fees and petroleum products levy.
\par <#/>He said the housing fund to be managed by the Treasury would start with 600m/- to be loaned to public and private developers who will build low cost houses for sale. <#/>The fund will draw resources from the payroll levy charged on employers.
\par <#/><ea/>Ndugu Kibona said the plots development revolving fund would be made of fees to be charged on land survey. <#/>The fund
 will be under the Ministry of Lands, Housing and Urban Development and would give priority to plots allocated under the housing fund. </I>
